<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-628-834  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 628 834.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Canadian Datasystems  June 1990 v22 n6 p21(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>&quot;The elephant can learn to dance.&quot; (IBM's situation in themicrocomputer market of the 1990s)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cary, Frank.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM plans to alter the function of microcomputers in the nextdecade by linking them with minicomputers and mainframes toproduce more efficient and convenient computing systems.andP;  Currentproducts, such as the OS/2 Extended Edition (OS/2 EE), allowapplications such as the Application Development/Cycle (AD/Cycle)to link PS/2 workstations to larger platforms.andP;  IBM expects SAA toconnect microcomputers to mainframes, making them intelligentworkstations that collectively process applications.andP;  Theseworkstations replace both independent microcomputers and dumbmainframe terminals.andP;  Linked mainframes and microcomputers handlemore users and data than networked microcomputers can, andretaining a central mainframe allows better high-level decisionmaking.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (planning).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     System DesignOutlookMicro-Mainframe CommunicationStrategic PlanningIntegrated Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>